Remarks. While examining the numerous material of this species from Australia and New Zealand , extreme variations were observed. The ocular acicles are frequently bifid ( Fig. 7a ). The armature of carpus and chela of the right cheliped, and carpi of walking legs, can be strong ( Fig. 7 c-f). On the 4th pereopod, the propodal rasp frequently exhibits two rows of ovate scales; the dactyl has a much longer, slenderer claw in females than in males (
Fig. 7g ,h
). The type of housing used also varies, in some specimens consisting of a gastropod shell, in others of a zoanthid. Variations were particularly pronounced in the New Zealand material, but with such a considerable amount of morphological overlap with specimens from other regions that there is no character, or suite of characters, that can be used to justify separation at the species level.
